snippet.textDisplay:
To be very frank, I wasn't very happy when Rohail, after delivering some of the most psychedelic and mystical songs post-NFAK, left Coke Studio and Strings took over. I wasn't very pleased with how Coke Studio used QB in their post-Rohail songs either, as good as those were. She always felt out of place, wrong song, wrong genre. But THIS... my God! This is pure sound, in the holiest of context. Divine, flowing with the essential Sufi longing, and devotion.
This and Tinak Dhin have been on repeat for days on end now, and I'm NOT getting bored! It'd be nice to hear QB and Ali Hamza sing together, please!!!

snippet.textDisplay: People seem to be pissed off on the drop after Dama Dam. Well I believe the magic of this song was just right there. The emphasis moved from Mast Qalandar to Dama Dam. From the master, to the breath of the disciple. Although I do not support the westernization of Traditional music, this rendition is unique in its own way. Psychedelic and mystic: just what sufi music could stand for.
